The Velvet Revolution was a non-violent revolution that took place in Czechoslovakia in 1989. It was a peaceful protest that was organized by the Civic Forum, a coalition of opposition groups. The revolution was sparked by the death of Jan Palach, a student who set himself on fire in protest of the Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968. The revolution was successful and led to the fall of communism in Czechoslovakia. The Velvet Revolution is considered one of the most important events in the history of Slovakia because it led to the establishment of democracy and the end of communist rule.
